choices.text:
a small moped with bodywork and a sidecar.

I think it's really interesting how different re-entry can be for people, but how fascinating we find it. Thanks for starting up this discussion, Zuckerman. It's awesome to hear about more returning - both from missions related things and other types of immersions.

A year is short :), in light of some NEH grants I've read.

Our grant proposals are due in 6 weeks and guess what is holding me up? diapers and bread and writing and laundry (the future is now). :)see y'all. No time to hang out online. no time to hang out in the RL.

70% of calls from friends in the field are from people dependent on a referee to understand the issues they face. (only 30% got it on their own).

I wonder if the same could be said for offers of help from friends and professional contacts.

One of the most helpful things about returning to the US has been the opportunity to communicate, in an honest, rational fashion, with inside-the-Beltway DC experts who are skeptical of the usefulness they could ever bring to development assistance. It's normal to have felt marginalized, excellent to find lots of people who recognize that cause, and incredibly awesome and different and healing to feel validated and not like a fool.

crits are coming in today as of 1AM. people thought the proposal was brilliant -- which was both nerve-wracking and encouraging.
